    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey prof, I'm stuck on this one sentence for my syntax assignment. \"The student saw the man with the telescope.\" In my tree diagram, the prepositional phrase \"with the telescope\" is attaching to the Verb Phrase (VP) instead of the Noun Phrase (NP). Can you explain why that attachment happens and what the structural difference looks like?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Attaching \"with the telescope\" to the VP suggests it's describing *how* the seeing happened—a manner or instrument. This is a classic case of **VP attachment**, meaning the phrase modifies the action of the verb \"saw.\" Structurally, this creates a structure where the prepositional phrase is a complement or adjunct to the VP, functioning like an adverbial modifier. If it were attached to the NP, it would modify \"man,\" suggesting the man possessed the telescope.",
      "source": "target",
